    {
      "citation_id": "[CITATION_4]",
      "span_text": "Similarly, the heterogeneous effects of past weather shocks on low versus high income counties would also not be predicted by a simple biology channel, as there is little reason to believe that the biological effect of weather on soil would vary in such a manner. To better understand the direct impact of weather variation on productivity and farmland values, we also interviewed directors and senior executives of the Farm Credit System. These interviewees stated that one season of hot weather does not affect soil quality, and further, that one would need three to four consecutive years of hot temperature to have any impact on soil Note again that all regressions are run with county fixed effects and so identification is not driven simply by the fact that low-income counties may be comprised of lower quality farmland that is more sensitive to weather shocks."
